Basics

All plots make using RMarkdown. Code is hidden using the echo = false flag, but it is available inside the markdown document.

Updates

  • Dec 2024: updated gender categories to reflect latest dataset nomenclature around Gender. Note: Some variables will change as gender terminology is updated in future data releases.

  • Oct 2023: first plots added

Font Public Sans Text size = 22 no background Titles bold background = by hex code.

Women in Stats potential

There are 22 rows

row_2_use = 2

look at some values:

data |> dplyr::filter(GEO == "Canada")|>
    # dplyr::filter(Highest.earned.degree %in% c("PhD (or any equivalent doctoral degree)","Masters","Bachelors"))|>
    dplyr::filter(Highest.earned.degree  == "PhD (or any equivalent doctoral degree)")|>
    dplyr::filter(Rank %in% c("Full professor","Associate professor", "Assistant professor")) |> 
    select(where(~ n_distinct(.) > 1))|> 
    mutate(Gender = str_replace_all(Gender, pattern = "\n", replacement = ""))|>
    dplyr::filter(Gender != "Total gender")|>
    dplyr::filter(Staff.functions == "Total staff function")|>
    dplyr::filter(Number.and.median == "Number of full time teaching staff")|> 
    dplyr::filter(Date == as_date("2022-07-01"))|> 
  select(Date,Rank,Gender,VALUE)|>
    group_by(Rank)|>
  mutate(Total_count = sum(VALUE))|>
  mutate(Proportion_gender = VALUE / Total_count)|>
  ungroup()
data |> dplyr::filter(GEO == "Canada")|>
    # dplyr::filter(Highest.earned.degree %in% c("PhD (or any equivalent doctoral degree)","Masters","Bachelors"))|>
    dplyr::filter(Highest.earned.degree  == "PhD (or any equivalent doctoral degree)")|>
    select(where(~ n_distinct(.) > 1))|> 
    dplyr::filter(Rank %in% c( "Assistant professor")) |> 
    # dplyr::filter(Rank %in% c("Full professor","Associate professor", "Assistant professor")) |> 
    mutate(Gender = str_replace_all(Gender, pattern = "\n", replacement = ""))|>
    dplyr::filter(Gender != "Total gender")|>
    dplyr::filter(Staff.functions == "Total staff function")|>
    dplyr::filter(Number.and.median == "Number of full time teaching staff")|> 
    dplyr::filter(Date >= as_date("2020-07-01"))|> 
  select(REF_DATE,Date,Rank,Gender,VALUE)|>
  # pivot_wider(names_from = Gender, values_from = VALUE)
    group_by(Rank,Date)|>
  mutate(Total_count = sum(VALUE))|>
  mutate(Proportion_gender = VALUE / Total_count)|>
  ungroup()
